[2] UK (Wales)
Date: Tue 21 Mar 2013
Source: Wales on lin e[edited]
http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/parents-urged-take-advantage-school-3903418


Parents urged to take advantage of school MMR clinics as measles cases rise again
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Public Health Wales has urged parents to attend school clinics before theycome to an end this week, with an extra 20 cases of measles confirmed in the last 5 days. MMR vaccination clinics in schools will come to an end this week.

Public Health Wales said an extra 20 cases had been confirmed in the ABMU, Hywel Dda and Powys health board areas in the past 5 days, taking the total in the Swansea epidemic to 1125. Throughout Wales there have now been 1325 cases since the start of November 2012 - compared with just 19 in 2011 [a 70-fold increase].

Vaccination sessions have been taking place in schools across the country, but are set to come to an end this week. Officials said there was a particular urgency for parents with children aged between 10-18 to make use of the sessions. Efforts to offer MMR vaccination throughout Wales have seen more than 50 000 people being vaccinated in the last 2 months. But fewer than a third of these were given to people aged between 10 and 18 -- the age group hardest hit by the outbreak.

Dr Marion Lyons, director of health protection for Public Health Wales, said: "This is the final week that children in schools across Wales will be offered the MMR vaccination, so parents whose children have not yet been fully vaccinated with 2 doses of MMR are reminded to complete the consent form to ensure the vaccine can be given. "Children over the age of 16 can consent to the vaccination without needing their parents to sign the form." The MMR is also available through GP surgeries, and more than 3500 doses of MMR have been given in Welsh GP surgeries in the last 7 days, which is a great sign that people are still coming forward for the vaccination.

"But those who would prefer to attend a school session rather than make a GP appointment are reminded that this is the last week they will be taking place, so now is the time to act." Meanwhile, drop-in vaccination sessions are also being held in the Powys on Saturday, 25 May 2013.

(By Julia McWatt)

